# TypeScript & Code Conventions

## TypeScript

- Strict mode enabled (`strict: true` in `tsconfig.json`), avoid `any`
- Use `unknown` for external/untrusted input and narrow safely
- Prefix genuinely unused variables with `_`
- Use `useId()` for generated element IDs
- Define prop interfaces explicitly; avoid `React.FC`
- Use `interface` for object shapes, `type` for unions/intersections/utilities

## Path Alias

All imports use the `@/` alias pointing to the project root:

```tsx
import { cn } from '@/lib/utils';
import siteConfig from '@/config/site';
import { getPosts } from '@/lib/post-utils';
import Anchor from '@/components/Anchor';
```

Never use relative `../../../` imports when `@/` works.

## Import Order

1. React and Next.js (framework-level)
2. Third-party libraries
3. `@/lib/*` utilities and hooks
4. `@/config/*`
5. `@/components/ui/*` (Shadcn primitives)
6. `@/components/*` (custom components)
7. Relative imports (same feature)
8. Type-only imports (`import type`)

### Example

```tsx
// 1. React / Next
import { useEffect, useId, useState } from 'react';
import type { Metadata } from 'next';
import { notFound } from 'next/navigation';

// 2. Third-party
import { motion } from 'motion/react';
import { format } from 'date-fns';
import { Home01Icon } from '@hugeicons/react';

// 3. Lib / hooks
import { cn } from '@/lib/utils';
import { getPosts } from '@/lib/post-utils';

// 4. Config
import siteConfig from '@/config/site';

// 5. Shadcn UI primitives
import { Button } from '@/components/ui/button';
import { Dialog } from '@/components/ui/dialog';

// 6. Custom components
import Anchor from '@/components/Anchor';
import { ScrambledText } from '@/components/ScrambledText';

// 7. Relative
import { MySubComponent } from './MySubComponent';

// 8. Types
import type { Post } from './types';
```

## ESLint Rules

- No `console.log` (error) — remove debug statements, use proper error handling
- React hooks rules enforced (`rules-of-hooks`, `exhaustive-deps`)
- Unused vars must be prefixed with `_`

## Prop Interfaces

Always define explicit prop interfaces:

```tsx
export interface CardProps {
  title: string;
  description?: string;
  href: string;
  className?: string;
}

const Card = ({ title, description, href, className }: CardProps) => {
  return (
    <a href={href} className={cn('rounded-lg border p-4', className)}>
      <h3 className="font-semibold">{title}</h3>
      {description && <p className="text-muted-foreground text-sm">{description}</p>}
    </a>
  );
};

export default Card;
```

## Server Component Typing

Use `Promise<PageProps>` for Next.js App Router page params:

```tsx
// app/posts/[slug]/page.tsx
export default async function Page({
  params,
}: {
  params: Promise<{ slug: string }>;
}) {
  const { slug } = await params;
  // ...
}
```

## Error Handling

Use `try/catch` with unknown narrowing. Never silently swallow errors:

```tsx
function getErrorMessage(error: unknown): string {
  if (error instanceof Error) return error.message;
  return 'Unexpected error';
}

try {
  const result = await riskyOperation();
} catch (error: unknown) {
  // handle or rethrow
  throw new Error(getErrorMessage(error));
}
```

## MDX Metadata Typing

Posts export a typed `metadata` object. Define and reuse the type in `lib/post-utils.ts`:

```tsx
type PostMetadata = {
  title: string;
  description: string;
  tags: string[];
  date: string; // 'YYYY-MM-DD'
};
```
